## Propagating Trace Context Through RabbitMQ

The issue is that RabbitMQ doesn't automatically carry W3C `traceparent`/`tracestate` headers. You need to manually inject context into message headers on publish and extract it on consume.

### Service A — Publisher (inject context)

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

// Define a shared ActivitySource
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceA.Messaging");

// When publishing:
using var activity = Source.StartActivity("OrderEvent Publish", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject current trace context into message headers
if (activity?.Context is ActivityContext ctx)
{
    props.Headers["traceparent"] = $"00-{ctx.TraceId}-{ctx.SpanId}-{(ctx.TraceFlags.HasFlag(ActivityTraceFlags.Recorded) ? "01" : "00")}";
    if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(activity.TraceStateString))
        props.Headers["tracestate"] = activity.TraceStateString;
}

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

### Service B — Consumer (extract context and link)

```csharp
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceB.Messaging");

// In your consumer callback:
void HandleMessage(IBasicProperties props, ReadOnlyMemory<byte> body)
{
    ActivityContext parentCtx = default;

    if (props.Headers?.TryGetValue("traceparent", out var raw) == true)
    {
        var traceparent = Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])raw);
        ActivityContext.TryParse(traceparent, null, out parentCtx);
    }

    // Start a new activity parented to the producer's context
    using var activity = Source.StartActivity(
        "OrderEvent Process",
        ActivityKind.Consumer,
        parentContext: parentCtx);

    // Your processing logic here...
}
```

### Wire up the ActivitySource in `Program.cs` (both services)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("ServiceA.Messaging")   // or ServiceB.Messaging
        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

**Key points:**
- The `traceparent` header is the W3C standard format that OTEL exporters understand.
- Using `parentContext` in `StartActivity` stitches the consumer span into the same trace as the producer.
- RabbitMQ headers store values as `byte[]`, so decode with `Encoding.UTF8.GetString` on the consumer side.

If you use **MassTransit**, it does this propagation automatically — no manual header work needed.
